<div class="cols head">
  <h1>Results</h1>
</div>


<div class="cols">
  <h2>Wet-Lab Results</h2>

  <h3>What we did (Build &rarr; Test)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Initial transformations (7/30):
      We transformed synthetic ZnuABC (clonal vector) into TOP10 and DH5α alongside pUC19 controls using a
      standard heat-shock workflow (15 min ice &rarr; 42&nbsp;°C 1 min &rarr; 5 min ice &rarr; SOC at 4&times; volume
      &rarr; 37&nbsp;°C 45 min outgrowth).
      <em>Result:</em> pUC19 produced strong colonies; synthetic ZnuABC plates yielded few to no colonies (mostly failed).
    </li>

    <li>
      Retry (8/2):
      We repeated DH5α + iZnuABC with the same conditions.
      <em>Result:</em> no colonies.
    </li>

    <li>
      BL21 attempt (8/4):
      We tested BL21 + iZnuABC at two DNA inputs (1&nbsp;µL and 10.5&nbsp;µL at 4&nbsp;ng/µL) with the same heat-shock and
      45 min outgrowth.
      <em>Result:</em> no colonies.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3>How this aligns with our Engineering Success plan</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Our plan notes pUC19 success but no colonies for pUPD3::synthetic ZnuABC on chloramphenicol (Cam) plates,
      pinpointing Cam selection as the failure point.
    </li>
    <li>
      We flagged that bacteriostatic Cam is sensitive to outgrowth time and recommend ~60 min SOC with shaking
      (we ran 45 min), plus a Cam gradient (12.5/25/34/50&nbsp;µg/mL) to test selection pressure.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Interpretation</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      The positive control verifies that our competent cells and workflow are sound; the systematic failure is
      specific to synthetic ZnuABC under Cam selection. The most likely causes are (a) Cam selection/outgrowth parameters and/or
      (b) vector integrity/quality, rather than a general transformation issue.
    </li>
    <li>
      Our 45 min outgrowth was likely insufficient for Cam (requires time for <em>cat</em> expression).
      Increasing to ~60 min with shaking is the evidence-based adjustment. Switching to BL21 did not rescue transformation,
      consistent with our guidance to stick with DH5α/TOP10 until the build is verified.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3>What this means for Engineering Success</h3>
  <p>We completed a Build–Test–Learn cycle:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Build: We ordered pUPD3::iZnuABC and performed transformations in multiple strains.</li>
    <li>Test: Controls worked; ZnuABC failed specifically under Cam selection.</li>
    <li>
      Learn: Extend Cam outgrowth, tune Cam concentration, verify plasmid integrity, and, if needed, electroporate.
      Then we can move to the Zincon uptake assay once we have confirmed colonies.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Next steps to unblock the assay</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Re-transform pUPD3::iZnuABC with SOC 60 min outgrowth (shaking); plate a
      Cam gradient (12.5/25/34/50&nbsp;µg/mL) plus a no-antibiotic recovery plate.
    </li>
    <li>Perform colony PCR across backbone/insert junctions on 2–4 colonies; archive glycerol stocks.</li>
    <li>
      If efficiency remains low, electroporate high-quality DNA (validated by digest/gel), then repeat step 1.
    </li>
    <li>
      With verified colonies, run the Zincon supernatant-depletion assay (AHL gradient; ZnSO₄ 25–50&nbsp;µM; read 620&nbsp;nm; no EDTA),
      including ΔznuB and empty-vector controls.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Bottom line</h3>
  <p>
    Our controls succeeded, but the Cam-selected synthetic ZnuABC build did not. Our planned fixes include longer Cam outgrowth,
    a Cam gradient, vector quality control, and potential electroporation. Once the build is stable, the Zincon assay will quantify
    AHL-tunable Zn²⁺ uptake and complete our experimental validation.
  </p>

  <p>
    <em>Source: Lab Notebook, iGEM - <i>Metlock</i> 2025
  </p>
</div>

